          <h2>Introduction</h2>
          <p align="justify">
          Narcissistic personality disorder is a condition in which a person has an inflated sense of self-importance, need to be admired, and extreme self-involvement.
          <br><br>
          <b>Alternative Names:</b>
God complex
          </p>
      </div>
      <div class="tabpage" id="tabpage_2">
          <h2>Causes & Risk Factors</h2>
          <p align="justify">
              How narcissistic personality develops in an individual is not known.<br>
              However, possible factors that have been proposed as causes include:<br>
              - Genetics<br>
- Disturbed childhood e.g. extremely high expectations, neglect
          </p>
      </div>
      <div class="tabpage" id="tabpage_3">
          <h2>Symptoms & Signs</h2>
          <p align="justify">
              Persons with narcissistic personality disorder usually have the following traits:<br>
- Are self-obsessed<br>
- Consider themselves better than others<br>
- Seek constant admiration<br>
- Like to be the centre of attraction<br>
- Fantasize about unlimited power, success, love etc.<br>
- Are often arrogant to others<br>
- Lack empathy for othersâ€™ feelings
          </p></div>
	  <div class="tabpage" id="tabpage_4">
              <h2>Treatment</h2>
              <p align="justify">
                  No medications have been recommended for the treatment of narcissistic personality disorder. Treatment is mainly based on psychotherapy. <br>
                  The types of psychotherapy include the following:<br>
                  1. Behavioural therapy<br>
                  2. Group therapy<br>
                  3. Family therapy<br>
Therapy sessions are required to be conducted for many years to effect any major change.    
              </p>    
